        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to observe the CO(4-3) and [CI] 1-0 emission lines from BX610 at z=2.2103. At this redshift, the CO(4-3) and [CI] 1-0 lines are shifted to 143.613 GHz and 153.307 GHz, respectively, and can be tuned in a single frequency setting with ALMA in band-4, since each line falls in a different IF. We would like to use the FDM mode with 1.875 GHz effective bandwidth per baseband, and using spectral averaging of 8x to lower the data rates. This leads to a total bandwidth of 7.5 GHz with independent channels of ~8 km/s. With this channel width, we will be able to search for clumps with narrow line-widths (~30 km/s). Each clump line will be thereby resolved into 3-4 channels.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to use ALMA in either of the C36-5 or C36-6 configurations in band-4 (~0.2-0.3" or 1.7-2.5 kpc resolution). These array configurations are best suited for observing the large scale rotating disk dynamics, while stil retaining information on the smaller scales, being essential to look for CO/[CI] emission that is dominated by one or several very high T_B regions on scales &lt;3 kpc.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The CO(4-3) and [CI] 1-0 lines for our target have recently been detected with the PdBI, showing bright emission, but at low-resolution (3"-5"; Aravena et al. in preparation). Hereby, we want to resolve the emission from these lines.

We base our sensitivity goal in the integrated flux of ~2 mJy peak for the [CI] 1-0 line, which is fainter than the CO(4-3) line recently obtained with the PdBI. From the resolved CO 1-0 observations and HST imaging (Forster-Schreiber et al. 2011), we expect the molecular gas emission to be distributed over a 15 kpc diameter disk (Fig. 2), with at least two bright clumps on scales ~2-3 kpc (Fig. 1). The line full-width at half maximum for CO is ~350 km/s. With this spatial distribution, for 50 km/s channels (close to the turbulent gas velocity dispersion), the [CI] 1-0 emission from clumps will have peak fluxes of &gt;1.5 mJy at 0.2'' resolution (very conservative). To detect this emission from clumps with significances of at least 6-sigma per 50 km/s channel (bandwidth used for sensitivity), we need to reach an rms level of 0.2 mJy per 50 km/s channel at the observing frequency of [CI] 1-0. For this, we require an on-source time of 1.55 hrs, or 3.34 hrs in total (including overheads and calibration). At this rms level, we will be able to significantly detect (&gt; 10-sigma) molecular gas clumps based on the strength of the integrated CO(4-3) line.

Detection of dust continuum at 2-mm: We calculate the expected 150 GHz continuum emission based on the estimated IR luminosity, (2.0+/-0.5) x 10^{12} Lsun, and using single component gray-body spectral energy distribution, with S_nu proportional to nu^(beta) B_nu(T_d) M_d, with M_d the dust mass and beta=1-2 the spectral index (Kovacs et al. 2006; Dunne et al. 2010). Since this galaxy has no indication of dominant AGN activity, we expect dust temperatures T_d~20-40 K (Dunne et al. 2010). Based on our target's molecular gas mass (~2x10^{11} M_sun and a wide range of gas-to-dust mass ratios of ~50-1000 (e.g. Devereux &amp; Young 1990; Wilson et al. 2008; Michalowski et al. 2010), we conservatively expect M_d&gt;1x10^8 M_sun. For any model, that reproduces the IR luminosity within its uncertainties (30\%), we expect the integrated flux at 250 GHz to be &gt;100 micro-Jy. This will be detected at the &gt;10-sigma level in the requested time (noise level 12 micro-Jy), however we expect this to be divided into a few bright star forming clumps.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
