        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to observe the CO(7-6) and [CI] 2-1 emission lines from BX610 at z=2.2103. At this redshift, the CO(7-6) and [CI] 2-1 lines are shifted to 251.269 GHz and 252.108 GHz, respectively, and can be tuned in a single frequency setting with ALMA in band-6, since both lines can be covered by a single spectral window. We would like to use the FDM mode with 1.875 GHz effective bandwidth per baseband, and using spectral averaging of 16x to lower the data rates. This leads to a total bandwidth of 7.5 GHz with independent channels of ~10 km/s. With this channel width, we will be able to search for clumps with narrow line-widths (~30 km/s). Each clump line will be thereby resolved into 3 channels. 

With the current spectral setup, we are also able to cover the frequencies of the HCO+(9-8) and H2O 2(1,1)-2(0,1) lines at 249.963 GHz and 234.256 GHz, respectively. Both lines are tracers of the densest regions of star-formation and a detection or limits will allow us to constrain the existence of such dense regions in the galaxy's ISM. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
