        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The CO(7-6) and [CI] 2-1 lines for our target have recently been detected with the PdBI, showing bright emission, but at low-resolution (2"; Aravena et al. in preparation). Hereby, we want to resolve the emission from these lines.

We base our sensitivity goal in the integrated flux of ~4 mJy peak for the [CI] 2-1 line (after subtracting the ~1 mJy continuum), which has about the same flux than the CO(7-6) line (Fig. 1). From the resolved CO 1-0 observations and HST imaging (Forster-Schreiber et al. 2011), we expect the molecular gas emission to be distributed over a 15 kpc diameter disk (Fig. 2), with at least two bright clumps on scales ~2-3 kpc (Fig. 1). The line full-width at half maximum for CO is ~350 km/s. With this spatial distribution, for 50 km/s channels (close to the turbulent gas velocity dispersion), the [CI] and CO emission from clumps will have peak fluxes of &gt;1.5 mJy at 0.2'' resolution (very conservative). To detect this emission from clumps with significances of at least 5-sigma per 50 km/s channel (bandwidth used for sensitivity), we need to reach an rms level of 0.3 mJy per 50 km/s channel at the observing frequency of the requested lines. For this, we require an on-source time of 1.18 hrs, or 2.17 hrs in total (including overheads and calibration). At this rms level, we will be able to significantly detect (&gt; 10-sigma) molecular gas clumps based on the strength of the integrated CO(4-3) line.

Detection of dust continuum at 1-mm: The integrated continuum flux as measured by the PdBI is of the order of 1 mJy (Fig. 1). This will provide a highly significantly detected integrated emission (55-sigma). We will thus be able to provide a resolved image of the star-forming regions in the galaxy. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
